etymologies: late Old English ceallian, from Old Norse kalla ‘summon loudly’

definitions: give (an infant or animal) a specified name

examples.text: they called their daughter Hannah

definitions: have a specified name

examples.text: she is called Eva
a 1942 mystery called Time To Kill

definitions: address or refer to (someone) by a specified name, title, endearment, or term of abuse

examples.text: please call me Lucy
if he remains quiet she calls him a wimp

definitions: refer to, consider, or describe (someone or something) as being

examples.text: he's the only person I would call a friend

definitions: cry out (a word or words)

examples.text: he heard an insistent voice calling his name
Meredith was already calling out a greeting

definitions: cry out to (someone) in order to summon them or attract their attention

examples.text: she heard Terry calling her
I distinctly heard you call

definitions: (of an animal, especially a bird) make its characteristic cry

examples.text: overhead, a skylark called

definitions: shout out or chant (the steps and figures) to people performing a square dance or country dance.
make (a particular bid) during the auction

examples.text: her partner called 6♠

definitions: claim (a privilege) for oneself, typically by shouting out a particular word or set phrase

examples.text: I call first dibs on the bathroom

shortDefinitions: claim specified privilege by shouting out word or phrase

definitions: contact or attempt to contact (a person or number) by phone

examples.text: could I call you back?
at the first sign of heart attack symptoms call 911 immediately

definitions: use a phone to summon (someone or something, especially an emergency service or a taxi)

examples.text: her husband called an ambulance

definitions: order or request the attendance of

examples.text: representatives of all three teams have been called to appear before the stewards
I got a letter calling me for an interview

definitions: bring (a witness) into court to give evidence

examples.text: four expert witnesses were called

shortDefinitions: bring witness into court to give evidence

definitions: draw critical attention to someone's unacceptable actions or behavior

examples.text: she called him on his claim that the media were doing a bad job of covering the economy

shortDefinitions: draw critical attention to someone's unacceptable actions

definitions: cause (someone) to have a strong urge to choose a particular career or way of life

examples.text: he was called to the priesthood
I think teachers, really good teachers, are called to teach

shortDefinitions: cause to have strong urge to choose particular way of lifeinspire

definitions: announce or decide that (an event, especially a meeting, strike, or election) is to happen

examples.text: there appeared to be no alternative but to call a general election
the Allied forces called a ceasefire
she intends to call a meeting of the committee early next week

shortDefinitions: announce or decide that meeting, election, etc. is to happen

definitions: (of a person) pay a brief visit

examples.text: he had promised Celia he would call in at the clinic
he called around last night looking for you

definitions: (of an umpire or other official in a game) pronounce (a ball, stroke, or other action) to be the thing specified

examples.text: the linesman called the ball wide

definitions: predict the result of (a future event, especially an election or a vote)

examples.text: in the Northeast, the race remains too close to call
few pundits risked calling the election for either Bush or Kerry

definitions: guess (the outcome) of tossing a coin

examples.text: Burnley called heads and won the toss
“You call,” he said. “Heads or tails?”

definitions: cause (a subroutine) to be executed

examples.text: one subroutine may call another subroutine (or itself)

phrases.text: call someone or something to mind
call someone or something to order
don't call us, we'll call you

definitions: a cry made as a summons or to attract someone's attention

examples.text: a nearby fisherman heard their calls for help
in response to the call, a figure appeared

definitions: a series of notes sounded on a brass instrument as a signal to do something

examples.text: a bugle call to rise at 5:30

definitions: a direction in a square dance given by the caller.
a bid, response, or double

examples.text: the alternative call of 2♠ would be quite unsound

definitions: the characteristic cry of a bird or other animal

examples.text: it is best distinguished by its call, a loud “pwit”

definitions: a device used to imitate the cry of a particular bird or other animal

examples.text: turkeys in the wild don't sound like most turkey calls
he bought a duck call at the store
most hunters I know have at least one call tucked away in a pocket

shortDefinitions: device used to imitate cry of bird

definitions: an instance of speaking to someone on the phone or attempting to contact someone by phone

examples.text: I'll give you a call at around five
he stopped returning her calls
a ten-minute call to the emergency services

shortDefinitions: instance of speaking to someone by phone

definitions: a brief social visit

examples.text: we paid a call on Howard

definitions: a visit or journey made by a doctor or other professional in response to a request for help, especially in an emergency situation

examples.text: the ambulance is out on a call
the district nurse used to make her calls on a bicycle

definitions: an appeal or demand for something to happen or be done

examples.text: the call for action was welcomed
a call to all sides to remain calm and refrain from violence
there are more and more calls on his time

definitions: demand or need for (goods or services)

examples.text: there was little call for work as sophisticated as his

definitions: an order or request for someone to be present

examples.text: he was delighted that so many former players had heeded the call to attend the conference

definitions: a vocation

examples.text: feeling the call to ministry, I started looking for a Bible college

definitions: a powerful force of attraction

examples.text: hikers can't resist the call of the Sierras

definitions: (in sports) a decision or ruling made by an umpire or other official, traditionally conveyed by a shout, that the ball has gone out of play or that a rule has been breached

examples.text: he was visibly irritated with the umpire's calls

definitions: a decision, judgement, or prediction

examples.text: personally, I'm all in favor, but it's your call
that entrepreneurial instinct may account for his ability to make tough calls when profits are at stake
the two old foes are so evenly matched that it's anyone's call

definitions: a command to execute a subroutine

examples.text: parameter values may be changed by calls to a special purpose input specification subroutine

definitions: a demand for payment of lent or unpaid capital.

crossReferenceMarkers: Compare with well (sense 4 of the noun)
definitions: (in a bar, club, etc.) denoting or made with relatively expensive brands of liquor which customers request by name.

examples.text: $6 call liquor drinks

shortDefinitions: denoting or made with relatively expensive brands of alcohol

phrases.text: call someone or something to mind
call someone or something to order
don't call us, we'll call you
